snippet.title: XEV 9e Uses Advanced Noise Cancellation To Block All Sound From Outside The Vehicle üîä #automobile
snippet.description:
The Mahindra XEV 9e promises a cabin so quiet it feels like the outside world disappears.

Marketing claims suggest "advanced noise cancellation" that blocks all external sound.

In reality, the SUV doesn't use traditional active noise cancellation with microphones and counter-waves.

Instead, it relies on passive noise isolation with acoustic laminated glass and smart material choices.

A 16-speaker Harman Kardon system with A.R. Rahman-composed "sonic themes" enhances the experience.

The result is a refined, serene cabin built on solid engineering rather than electronic gimmicks.

What are your thoughts?

(via @j3vlogs_techinfo)

snippet.title: Racers face split-second decisions #shorts #trending #viral
snippet.description:
Racers face split-second decisions under extreme speeds, and clear vision becomes the difference between staying on track and going off-course. That‚Äôs exactly why visor technology plays such a vital role in motorsport performance and safety.

Modern racing visors are precision-engineered, using optical-grade polycarbonate that delivers both high impact resistance and crystal-clear clarity. That clarity matters when debris, glare, or weather conditions challenge your sight line. Many visors include anti-fog and anti-scratch coatings to keep your view sharp even when humidity rises or minor scratches threaten to blur your vision.

To tackle mud, rain, or dust‚Äîespecially in Formula 1‚Äîracing helmets often use layered tear-off films. You simply peel away a layer when your vision clouds. This system keeps your field of vision clean lap after lap without stopping your momentum. Some setups allow up to four layers that you remove one by one as needed.

Top-tier brands push the innovation even further. Racing Optics, for example, introduced laminated tear-offs that stack multiple thin layers yet still appear as one seamless surface. That preserves clarity throughout the race, and champions like Tony Stewart and Ricky Carmichael swear by this system because it stays clear no matter how many layers they peel away.

Bell Racing adds another layer of genius with its SmartLock‚Ñ¢ visor system. It allows one-handed locking and unlocking‚Äîyes, even with thick racing gloves on. That means you can adjust the visor quickly without distraction. The system debuted in real racing during the 2024 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix and already meets the latest FIA safety standards.

Beyond tear-offs and locking systems, visors now come in advanced options too. Photochromic visors darken in sunlight then lighten in shade. Mirrored and iridium coatings cut glare and enhance contrast on bright days. UV protection shields your eyes from harmful rays, while hydrophobic coatings and curved edges help rain bead off, keeping your vision soothed and focused
